description:
Many UI screens use bare 'on Object' to catch all exceptions and show a generic message:

```dart
} on Object {
  if (!mounted) return;
  setState(() {
    _busy = false;
    _error = l10n.errorGenericTitle;
  });
}
```

Acceptable in Flutter (no checked exceptions) and good for security (generic user-facing messages via errorGenericTitle), but it masks unexpected runtime errors and makes debugging harder.

Recommendation: in 'on Object' blocks, capture the error without surfacing it to users — e.g. FlutterError.reportError or an analytics/crash-reporting event — so unexpected errors are observable.

Files: multiple UI screens.
Source: code review finding #3 (Code Quality).
